<h2 id="faq">FAQ</h2>
<p><strong>Q: Is the Kobo Libra Colour a good replacement for a retired Kindle?</strong><br />A: Yes, for most users. The Kobo Libra Colour natively reads EPUB, KEPUB, PDF, MOBI, CBR, CBZ, HTML, RTF, and TXT, has a 7-inch color E-Ink Kaleido 3 screen at 300 ppi, physical page-turn buttons, and a 40-day battery. It syncs with the Kobo Store and Pocket integration out of the box. The only thing you lose is Amazon's Kindle ecosystem, but if you were already planning to leave, the Libra Colour is the cleanest 2026 alternative.</p>
<p><strong>Q: Can the PocketBook Era read Amazon Kindle books?</strong><br />A: Not directly. PocketBook Era supports EPUB, PDF, MOBI (read-only), DJVU, FB2, DOC, DOCX, HTML, RTF, TXT, PRC, and CHM. To read Kindle books on PocketBook you need to strip Amazon's DRM first using the Calibre + DeDRM plugin combination, then side-load via USB-C, microSD, email, or PocketBook Cloud. Note that stripping DRM may violate Amazon's terms in some jurisdictions. The Kobo and Boox devices do not require this step for non-Amazon books.</p>
<p><strong>Q: Which 2026 e-reader has the best battery life?</strong><br />A: Kobo Libra Colour wins on standby: about 100 days on standby, 40 days of regular reading. PocketBook Era is close: 70 days standby, 30 days reading. Kindle Paperwhite (current 2026 model) is rated for 10 weeks reading and 'months' standby, but Kindle's always-on Wi-Fi sync and Audible downloads cut that to 4-6 weeks for active users. All three are an order of magnitude better than phones or tablets for battery life.</p>
<p><strong>Q: Do all three e-readers support library borrowing (OverDrive/Libby)?</strong><br />A: Kobo Libra Colour has built-in OverDrive/Libby integration: sign in with your library card and borrow directly from the device, no computer needed. Kindle Paperwhite has Whispernet-style library borrowing via the Kindle Store, but the catalog is region-locked and smaller than Libby. PocketBook Era supports library borrowing through PocketBook Cloud or the built-in browser with OverDrive's web reader, but the experience is clunkier than Kobo's native integration. For library-heavy users, Kobo wins in 2026.</p>
<p><strong>Q: Is the PocketBook Era better than the Kobo Libra Colour for PDFs?</strong><br />A: Yes, by a meaningful margin. The PocketBook Era has a 7-inch E-Ink Carta 1200 screen (1264x1680, 300 ppi) and PocketBook's PDF reader includes reflow, text-to-speech, dictionary lookup, and zoom presets optimized for academic papers and scanned PDFs. The Kobo Libra Colour's PDF support is functional but not as refined. Kobo's strength is EPUB reflow, not fixed-layout PDF rendering. For users who read both novels and research papers, the PocketBook Era's PDF toolkit is a real differentiator.</p>
